    //custom thread pool
       @Aynsc in spring uses a default thread pool with single
    thread if we dont specify the thread pool. To execute it  on multiple threads custom thread pool should be created and  add it in @Async annotation.

        1. Create a configuration class that implements AsyncConfigurer with @EnableAsync and @Configuration.
        2. Override getAsyncExecutor()
        3.define ThreadPoolTaskExecutor with core size, max size of threads and queue capacity and set any name to thread myThread and initialize() it.

        @Aynsc(myThread) to be used in annotation if custom thread pool is used

      The asynchronous processing in Java is similar to other languages. 
    1. In other language Async tasks, its executed in non blocking way. The main thread is not blocked till the execution completes. 
    Java Futures are blocking by default , but non blocking way can be achieved by using Completable Future.

When you concatenate strings using + operator, compiler translates concatenation code to use `StringBuffer` for better performance. In order to improve performance `StringBuffer` is the better choice.

The quickest way of concatenate two string using + operator.

    String str = &quot;Java&quot;;
    str = str + &quot;Tutorial&quot;;

The compiler translates this code as:

    String s1 = &quot;Java&quot;;
    StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer(s1);
    sb.append(&quot;Tutorial&quot;);
    s1 = sb.toString();

So it is better to use `StringBuffer` OR `String.format` for concatenation

Using `String.format`   

    String s = String.format(&quot;%s %s&quot;, &quot;Java&quot;, &quot;Tutorial&quot;);

